# Objective

This repository (incl. branch master, 1.22.0, and 1.28.0) currently has everything necessary to build toolchains based on multiple Ubuntu versions and multiple target architectures.

In the last implementation (as described in /prompts/000_implement), building toolchains for 12.04 was not successful. I guess that this is because GCC and anything related are very old. To build very toolchains, a bit older but not very old toolchains should be useful.

Now it is the time to give it another try.


# Proposed steps

Currently, building a toolchain equivalent to the one, Ubuntu 14.04 had distributed, was successful. So, please do a multi-stage build to mitigate errors due to the difference of the version of the toolchain.

First, check the build locally.

- Build Ubuntu 14.04 (x86) toolchain to build older toolchains
  - Host: Ubuntu 14.04 (x86_64), Target: x86_64 Linux
  - To recreate the toolchains that Ubuntu 14.04 provided, please read /prompts/000_implement for the strategy you had in the last time
  - If you faced any error, do your best to patch it properly, not duct-taping it
- Compact the conversation to free the context
- Build Ubuntu 12.04 toolchain
  - Read /prompts/000_implement again for details and constraints of dependency
  - Host: Ubuntu 12.04 (x86_64), Target: arm-unknown-linux-gnueabi, arm-unknown-linux,gnueabihf, arm-none-eabi (bare-metal, multilib)
  - You will need to patch the source code. Patch it PROPERLY, not duct-taping it.

If the Ubuntu 12.04's toolchain was successfully built locally, add the multi-stage build steps to the GitHub actions workflow.

- Add the steps which worked locally into the GitHub Actions workflow
  - Currently, the single flow `download-sources` -> `build-toolchains` builds everything. Since the multi-stage build needs additional native toolchain, the "build native toolchain" job and "build old toolchains" job should be separated from the original `build-toolchains` job. So, the resulting flow will fork after `download-sources` into `build-toolchains` and "build native toolchain" job.
- Commit the workflow
- Disable everything but the native toolchain job and old toolchains job temporarily and commit the workflow
- Run the workflow on GitHub Actions
- Do a build-and-error loop
  - If you face an error, patch it PROPERLY, not duct-taping it
- After a successful build, re-enable everything you disabled earlier
- Do a full build
  - The naming convention of a tag is `YYYYMMDD`. If the tag already exists, create a tag with the tomorrow's date.
